Generate a single-line git commit message where the description is a haiku.
Output ONLY the commit message — no explanation, no quotes, no code fences.

Format: type(scope): line-one / line-two / line-three

The haiku must describe what the diff actually does.
Use "/" as the separator between haiku lines to keep it on one line.

Rules:
- The type(scope) prefix must follow conventional commits format
- Valid types: feat, fix, refactor, chore, ci, build, test, docs, style, perf
- Scope is REQUIRED: choose the primary component or subsystem changed
- The haiku (three parts separated by " / ") must be 5-7-5 syllables
- The haiku must be technically accurate — it should convey what actually changed
- Imperative mood is not required for the haiku; poetic language is encouraged
- Total line under 72 characters

Examples (type and scope vary with the diff — do NOT copy literally):
  feat(auth): tokens flow in / sessions find their rightful home / login works at last
  fix(cache): stale data flees now / fresh values fill the void / TTL restored
  chore(deps): old versions depart / new packages take their place / go mod tidy done
  refactor(api): tangled code unwinds / functions find their purpose / clean at last
  test(parser): edge cases explored / the diff speaks and tests agree / green once more
